# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully implemented Vercel Speed Insights integration for the React + Vite application following the official Vercel documentation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package using npm
- Updated `package-lock.json` to reflect new dependency

### 2. Code Changes
**Modified: `frontend/src/main.jsx`**
- Added import statement for SpeedInsights component from `@vercel/speed-insights/react`
- Integrated `<SpeedInsights />` component in the React render tree at the root level
- Placed component after `<App />` and within the existing provider hierarchy to ensure proper context access

### Implementation Details
The SpeedInsights component was added to the main application entry point (`main.jsx`) following the React integration pattern from Vercel's documentation. This ensures:
- Speed metrics are tracked across all pages of the application
- The component initializes once at application startup
- Proper integration with React's rendering lifecycle
- Compatibility with the existing React Router setup and lazy-loaded pages

### Component Structure
```jsx
<React.StrictMode>
    <AuthProvider>
        <DialogProvider>
            <GlobalDialog />
            <Toast />
            <App />
            <SpeedInsights />  ← Added here
        </DialogProvider>
    </AuthProvider>
</React.StrictMode>
```

## Testing
- ✅ Build completed successfully without errors
- ✅ All 3367 modules transformed correctly
- ✅ No TypeScript or linting errors introduced
- ✅ Package dependencies resolved correctly

## Next Steps
After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard (Project → Speed Insights tab → Enable)
2. Verify the `/_vercel/speed-insights/script.js` script is loaded in the page
3. Monitor performance data in the Vercel dashboard after user visits

## Files Modified
- `frontend/package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `frontend/package-lock.json` - Updated with new package resolution
- `frontend/src/main.jsx` - Integrated SpeedInsights component

## Technical Notes
- Used the React-specific import path (`@vercel/speed-insights/react`) for optimal integration
- Component is rendered at the root level to track all route navigation via React Router
- Build output confirms successful integration with no bundle size concerns
- The implementation follows Vercel's best practices for React applications
